      "### Page 56",
      "Encoder-Decoder (background)",
      "â€¢ They are DNN architectures that are widely used in sequence-to-",
      "sequence problems.",
      "â€¢ For example, in: machine translation, text generation, text",
      "summarization, and also in audio.",
      "â€¢ Encoder-Decoder networks are especially effective for tasks where",
      "the input and output are of variable length.",
      "â€¢ They handle input and output sequences flexibly, capturing the",
      "relevant information in the latent representation and generating",
      "coherent output sequences.",
      "![Page 56, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 3 KERAS-images/Chapter 3 KERAS_page_056.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 57",
      "Structure",
      "â€¢ Encoder:",
      "â€¢ The task of the encoder is to transform the input (e.g., a sequence of words in",
      "a language) into a lower-dimensional but more meaningful latent",
      "representation or feature vector.",
      "â€¢ Each time step (or word) in the input is processed and encoded into an",
      "internal representation. Important information is captured in the latent",
      "representation.",
      "â€¢ Upon completion of the input sequence, the encoder produces a single vector",
      "(or set of vectors) that captures the key information of the input.",
      "![Page 57, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 3 KERAS-images/Chapter 3 KERAS_page_057.png)",
      "![Page 57, Figure 2](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 3 KERAS-images/Chapter 3 KERAS_page_057_img_001.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 58",
      "Structure",
      "â€¢ Decoder:",
      "â€¢ The decoder takes the latent vector generated by the encoder and uses it to",
      "generate the desired output (for example, a sequence of words in another",
      "language).",
      "â€¢ It starts by generating the first part of the output using the latent vector and",
      "then, at each subsequent time step, incorporates information from the latent",
      "vector and the output generated up to that point.",
      "â€¢ The output is generated step by step and is adjusted based on the",
      "information learned by the encoder.",
      "![Page 58, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 3 KERAS-images/Chapter 3 KERAS_page_058.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 59",
      "Training",
      "â€¢ During the training phase, the network is fed known input-output",
      "pairs.",
      "â€¢ The network learns to adjust the weights of its connections such that",
      "the output generated by the decoder is as close as possible to the",
      "desired output, taking into account the information captured by the",
      "encoder.",
      "â€¢ A loss function is used to measure the discrepancy between the",
      "generated output and the desired output. This function guides the",
      "model during training to minimize error.",
      "![Page 59, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 3 KERAS-images/Chapter 3 KERAS_page_059.png)",
