      "",
      "### Page 22",
      "Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)",
      "Imagine you need to convert audio to text. The main problem is:",
      "â€¢ Audio is long (many frames)",
      "â€¢ Words aren't aligned with specific moments",
      "â€¢ We don't know exactly which part of audio corresponds to each letter",
      "CTC solves this:",
      "1. Allows the system to \"guess\" where letters go",
      "2. Uses a special symbol (blank) to:",
      "1. Separate repeated letters",
      "2. Fill spaces where there are no letters",
      "Practical example:",
      "â€¢ Audio says \"hello\"",
      "â€¢ System might predict: \"h-e-ll-o-â€œ          (where \"-\" is the blank symbol)",
      "â€¢ It could also be: \"-h-eell-oo-\"",
      "â€¢ All these variations convert to \"hello\"",
      "![Page 22, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 6 SPEECH-images/Chapter 6 SPEECH_page_022.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 23",
      "Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)",
      "â€¢ All these paths for â€œhelloâ€ are valid. Each frame in a path has a probability -",
      "how confident the system is about that guess.",
      "â€¢ The scoring works like this:",
      "1.For each path, multiply the probabilities of each guess",
      "2.Add up all the path probabilities that lead to the correct word",
      "3.Higher total probability means the system is doing a good job",
      "â€¢ During training, if the total probability is low, the system adjusts to make better",
      "guesses next time. It's like learning to recognize patterns: the more examples it",
      "sees, the better it gets at matching sounds to letters.",
      "â€¢ Think of it like multiple people trying to write down what they hear. Some might",
      "write it slightly differently, but as long as it reads correctly when cleaned up, it's",
      "considered correct. The system learns which ways of hearing and writing are",
      "most reliable.",
      "![Page 23, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 6 SPEECH-images/Chapter 6 SPEECH_page_023.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 24",
      "Attention Mechanisms in ASR",
      "1.Basic Concept",
      "â€¢ Helps model focus on relevant parts of audio",
      "â€¢ Creates dynamic connections between encoder and decoder",
      "â€¢ Learns where to \"pay attention\" in input sequence",
      "â€¢ Solves alignment problems better than CTC",
      "2.How It Works",
      "â€¢ Encoder processes audio into features",
      "â€¢ Decoder generates text one symbol at time",
      "â€¢ Attention scores relevant audio parts for each output",
      "â€¢ Weighted sum creates context for prediction",
      "â€¢ Updates focus as it generates each character",
      "![Page 24, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 6 SPEECH-images/Chapter 6 SPEECH_page_024.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 25",
      "Types of Attention",
      "â€¢ Bahdanau Attention:",
      "â€¢ Additive attention",
      "â€¢ Uses separate neural network",
      "â€¢ Computes alignment scores with learned weights",
      "â€¢ Better for varying length sequences",
      "â€¢ More flexible but computationally intensive",
      "â€¢ Luong Attention:",
      "â€¢ Multiplicative attention",
      "â€¢ Simpler, faster computation",
      "â€¢ Direct dot product between states",
      "â€¢ Works well for similar length sequences",
      "â€¢ More memory efficient",
      "![Page 25, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 6 SPEECH-images/Chapter 6 SPEECH_page_025.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 26",
      "Key Advantages of attention",
      "1. \"Better handling of long sequences\"",
      "â€¢ Imagine listening to a long sentence. Regular systems might forget the beginning by the time they reach the end",
      "â€¢ Attention is like taking notes - it can look back at any part whenever needed",
      "â€¢ Works better for long speeches or complex sentences",
      "2. \"No monotonic alignment assumption\"",
      "â€¢ Old systems assumed words must be processed strictly left to right",
      "â€¢ Attention is more like how humans understand speech - we can connect related parts even if they're far apart",
      "â€¢ Example: In \"The cat, which I saw yesterday, is black\", attention can link \"cat\" with \"is black\" even with words in between",
      "3. \"Can attend to multiple parts of input\"",
      "â€¢ Like having multiple sticky notes while listening",
      "â€¢ Can focus on several important parts at once",
      "â€¢ Example: When hearing \"twenty-three\", it can look at both parts together to understand it's \"23\"",
      "4. \"Helps with noisy or unclear speech\"",
      "â€¢ Like having the ability to \"double-check\" unclear parts",
      "â€¢ If one part is unclear, can use context from other parts",
      "â€¢ Similar to how we understand someone speaking in a noisy room",
      "5. \"Provides interpretable alignment visualization\"",
      "â€¢ We can see what parts of speech the system is focusing on",
      "â€¢ Like highlighting the words as they're being processed",
      "â€¢ Helps understand how the system makes decisions",
      "![Page 26, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 6 SPEECH-images/Chapter 6 SPEECH_page_026.png)",
      "",
