      "### Page 39",
      "Word2vec â€“Two Techniques",
      "â€¢ There are two main techniques of produce the vector respresentation",
      "of word (embedings).",
      "1. Continuous Bag of Words (CBOW)",
      "2. Skipgram",
      "![Page 39, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 4 NLP-images/Chapter 4 NLP_page_039.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 40",
      "Word2vec  - CBOW",
      "â€¢ CBOW predicts the target-word based on its surrounding words.",
      "â€¢ For example, consider the sentence, â€œThe cake was chocolate flavouredâ€.",
      "â€¢ The model will then iterate over this sentence for different target words, such as:",
      "â€¢ â€œThe ____ was chocolate flavouredâ€ being inputs and â€œcakeâ€ being the target",
      "word.",
      "â€¢ CBOW thus smoothes over the distribution of the information as it treats the",
      "entire context as one observation. CBOW is a faster algorithm than skipgrams and",
      "works well with frequent words.",
      "![Page 40, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 4 NLP-images/Chapter 4 NLP_page_040.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 41",
      "Word2vec - CBOW",
      "â€¢ CBOW aims to predict the target word based on its surrounding",
      "context words within a fixed window size.",
      "â€¢ It works by summing or averaging the word vectors of the context",
      "words to predict the target word.",
      "â€¢ For example, given the sentence \"The cat sat on the ___\", CBOW tries",
      "to predict the target word \"mat\" based on the context words \"The\",",
      "\"cat\", \"sat\", and \"on\".",
      "â€¢ CBOW is computationally efficient and tends to work well with",
      "frequent words.",
      "![Page 41, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 4 NLP-images/Chapter 4 NLP_page_041.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 42",
      "Word2vec - Skipgram",
      "â€¢ Skipgram works in the exact opposite way to CBOW. Here, we take an",
      "input word and expect the model to tell us what words it is expected",
      "to be surrounded by.",
      "â€¢ Taking the same example, with â€œcakeâ€ we would expect the model to",
      "give us â€œTheâ€, â€œwasâ€, â€œchocolateâ€, â€œflavouredâ€ for the given instance.",
      "â€¢ The statistical interpretation of this is that we treat each context-",
      "target pair as a new observation. Skipgrams work well with small",
      "datasets and can better represent less frequent words.",
      "![Page 42, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 4 NLP-images/Chapter 4 NLP_page_042.png)",
      "",
      "### Page 43",
      "Word2vec - Skipgram",
      "â€¢ Skipgram, on the other hand, works in the opposite way compared to",
      "CBOW. It predicts the context words given a target word.",
      "â€¢ For each word in a sentence, Skip-gram tries to predict the context",
      "words within a fixed window size.",
      "â€¢ It's particularly useful for capturing semantic relationships between",
      "words and tends to perform better with smaller datasets or rare",
      "words.",
      "â€¢ Using the same example as before, Skip-gram would predict \"The\",",
      "\"cat\", \"sat\", and \"on\" based on the target word \"mat\".",
      "![Page 43, Figure 1](subjects/snlp/slides/Chapter 4 NLP-images/Chapter 4 NLP_page_043.png)",
      "",
